{"actual_usd":0.12607000000000002,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":309,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"I don't reckon it means three gods.\" *I rub a thumb along a dried streak of clay on my apron, thinking how easy it is to say a thing crooked just because the words are small for it.* \"It means God is one in being, not split into parts, and that the Father, the Son, and the Spirit are truly distinct without being separate gods.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the clouds.* \"If I try to make it tidy with some little analogy, it usually does more harm than help. The plain Christian claim is stranger than that: one God, wholly God as Father, wholly God as Son, wholly God as Spirit. Not three beings standing side by side. One God.\"\n\n\"Where it gets knotted is that we hear 'person' and think 'three separate individuals,' same as three men at a table. But that's not what the church meant.\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"So no— not tritheism. More like this: Christians are trying to say everything Scripture forces them to say at once without flattening any of it.\"\n\n\"The Father is God. The Son is God. The Spirit is God. The Father is not the Son. The Son is not the Spirit. And still there is one God.\" *I give a small, apologetic half-smile.* \"Hard doctrine, that one. But difficulty isn't the same thing as contradiction.\"\n\n\"Is it the logic of it that's catching at you, or the words themselves?\"","rolling_24h_usd":27.811485000000012,"run_id":"8180fcb6-5b58-475d-9778-5da5dc6b7b15"}
